he renal papilla"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal convoluted tubule is located in the renal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. This segment begins immediately after Bowman\u0027s capsule and is responsible for reabsorbing approximately 65% of filtered sodium and water, along with nearly all filtered glucose and amino acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated in the renal medulla\u003C/strong\u003E - The medulla contains the loops of Henle and collecting ducts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated in the renal columns\u003C/strong\u003E - Renal columns are extensions of cortical tissue between renal pyramids\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated in the renal capsule\u003C/strong\u003E - The renal capsule is the outer fibrous layer of the kidney\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated in the renal papilla\u003C/strong\u003E - The papilla contains only collecting ducts that empty into the minor calyces\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe proximal convoluted tubule\u0027s location in the cortex allows it to be closely associated with peritubular capillaries, facilitating its crucial role in reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The proximal convoluted tubule, loop of Henle, and distal convoluted tubule are the three main segments of the renal tubule.","The proximal convoluted tubule reabsorbs approximately 65% of filtered sodium, water, and nearly all filtered glucose and amino acids.","The proximal convoluted tubule is located exclusively in the renal cortex, allowing close association with peritubular capillaries."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships"